global health, human rights, and more. Assembling a group of top scholars, the editors are able to provide a wide-ranging yet coherent survey of contemporary international institutions and how they are governed. In the process, they offer a useful basis for understanding the financial crisis of 2008. Relations of Global Power is the only book available that examines the many different dimensions of the international regulatory structure across a range of issues, placing them all within the context of neoliberal globalization. It will be of interest to scholars of political science, sociology, policy studies, public administration, and global studies, and will also appeal to activists and members of alter-globalization movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInternational economic relations. 0aInternational organization. 0aInternational relations. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aRelations economiques internationales. 4aCoursebook. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aCoburn, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoburn, Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, A. Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCypher, James M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKotz, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcBride, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMcBride, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRussell, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSingh, Kavaljit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1